<subSubSection pageId="56" pageNumber="179" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="56" pageNumber="179">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="56" pageNumber="179">We honour Dr. Konstantin Romaschenko (born 1969) who accompanied PMP and Robert J. Soreng on the collecting trip in which material of the species was gathered.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="56" pageNumber="179" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="56" pageNumber="179">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="56" pageNumber="179">
<taxonomicName authorityName="P. M. Peterson" authorityYear="2018" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia romaschenkoi" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="romaschenkoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">Muhlenbergia romaschenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be separated from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. microsperma" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="microsperma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">M. microsperma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having longer acute to acuminate glumes (1-2.8 mm long) and by lacking cleistogamous panicles present in the axils of the lower sheaths. 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia tenuifolia" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tenuifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">Muhlenbergia tenuifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Kunth) Kunth, a species ranging from southern Arizona, New Mexico and Texas, U.S.A., throughout 
<normalizedToken originalValue="México">Mexico</normalizedToken>
and then again in Venezuela, Bolivia and Argentina, is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. romaschenkoi" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="romaschenkoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">M. romaschenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs in having yellowish anthers 0.9-1.5 mm long (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/25027794" author="Peterson, PM" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany Monographs" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" pagination="1 - 109" refId="B25" refString="Peterson, PM, Annable, CR, 1991. Systematics of the annual species of Muhlenbergia (Poaceae - Eragrostideae). Systematic Botany Monographs 31: 1 - 109, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/25027794" title="Systematics of the annual species of Muhlenbergia (Poaceae - Eragrostideae)." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/25027794" volume="31" year="1991">Peterson and Annable 1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Peterson, PM" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" refId="B24" refString="Peterson, PM, 2003. 17.33 Muhlenbergia Schreb. In: Barkworth ME, Capels KM, Long S, Piep MB (Eds) Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 2 Flora of North America North of Mexico, Vol 25. Oxford University Press, New York, 145-201." title="17.33 Muhlenbergia Schreb. In: Barkworth ME, Capels KM, Long S, Piep MB (Eds) Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 2 Flora of North America North of Mexico, Vol 25. Oxford University Press, New York, 145 - 201." year="2003">Peterson 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Peterson, P" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Botanical Research Institute of Texas" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" pagination="933 - 1000" refId="B36" refString="Peterson, P, Valdes-Reyna, J, Herrera Arrieta, Y, 2007b. Muhlenbergiinae (Poaceae: Chloridoideae: Cynodonteae): from northeastern Mexico. Journal of the Botanical Research Institute of Texas 1: 933 - 1000" title="Muhlenbergiinae (Poaceae: Chloridoideae: Cynodonteae): from northeastern Mexico." volume="1" year="2007 b">Peterson et al. 2007b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Peterson, PM" journalOrPublisher="Caldasia" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" pagination="21 - 54" refId="B28" refString="Peterson, PM, Giraldo-Canas, D, 2011. Las especies de Muhlenbergia (Poaceae: Chloridoideae) de Argentina. Caldasia 33: 21 - 54" title="Las especies de Muhlenbergia (Poaceae: Chloridoideae) de Argentina." volume="33" year="2011">
Peterson and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Giraldo-Cañas">Giraldo-Canas</normalizedToken>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Peterson, PM" journalOrPublisher="Caldasia" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" refId="B29" refString="Peterson, PM, Giraldo-Canas, D, 2012. Muhlenbergia Schreb. In: Zuloaga FO, Rugolo ZE, Anton AMR (Eds) Flora Argentina, Flora Vascular de la Republica Argentina, Vol. 3, Tomo 1, Monocotyledoneae, Poaceae: Aristidoideae a Pharoideae. IBODA-IMBIV, CONICET, Buenos Aires, Argentina, 140-154." title="Muhlenbergia Schreb. In: Zuloaga FO, Rugolo ZE, Anton AMR (Eds) Flora Argentina, Flora Vascular de la Republica Argentina, Vol. 3, Tomo 1, Monocotyledoneae, Poaceae: Aristidoideae a Pharoideae. IBODA-IMBIV, CONICET, Buenos Aires, Argentina, 140 - 154." year="2012">2012</bibRefCitation>
). Initially we thought the new species was 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. tenuiofolia" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="tenuiofolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">M. tenuiofolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with immature anthers 0.3-0.4 mm long. However, our collection of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. romaschenkoi" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="romaschenkoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">M. romaschenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes well-developed florets with mature caryopses and anthers. Therefore, the observed small anthers in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. romaschenkoi" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="romaschenkoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">M. romaschenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are not a result of immaturity but represent a genetic difference, from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. tenuifolia" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="tenuifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">M. tenuifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is not known in Peru.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="56" pageNumber="179">
<taxonomicName authorityName="P. M. Peterson" authorityYear="2018" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia romaschenkoi" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="romaschenkoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">Muhlenbergia romaschenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a member of 
<taxonomicName authority="subg. Muhlenbergia" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" infraspecific-rank="subg." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M." order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus" subGenus="Muhlenbergia">M. subg. Muhlenbergia</taxonomicName>
, is sister to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. spiciformis" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="spiciformis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">M. spiciformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Trin. (plastid marker), a species known from south-western United States and throughout Mexico whereas ITS marker aligns it within the 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. tenuifolia" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="tenuifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">M. tenuifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A, B Maximum-likelihood tree inferred from combined plastid (ndhA intron, rps 16 - trnK, rps 16 intron, rps 3, and rpl 32 - trnL) and ITS sequences. Thick branches indicate posterior probabilities of 0.95 - 1; species in red occur in South America; scale bar = 2 %." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.114.28799.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/254042" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">1B</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia spiciformis" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spiciformis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">Muhlenbergia spiciformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the new species in having shorter glumes 0.3-1 mm long and larger anthers 0.9-1.6 mm long (
<bibRefCitation author="Peterson, PM" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" refId="B24" refString="Peterson, PM, 2003. 17.33 Muhlenbergia Schreb. In: Barkworth ME, Capels KM, Long S, Piep MB (Eds) Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 2 Flora of North America North of Mexico, Vol 25. Oxford University Press, New York, 145-201." title="17.33 Muhlenbergia Schreb. In: Barkworth ME, Capels KM, Long S, Piep MB (Eds) Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 2 Flora of North America North of Mexico, Vol 25. Oxford University Press, New York, 145 - 201." year="2003">Peterson 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Peterson, P" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Botanical Research Institute of Texas" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" pagination="933 - 1000" refId="B36" refString="Peterson, P, Valdes-Reyna, J, Herrera Arrieta, Y, 2007b. Muhlenbergiinae (Poaceae: Chloridoideae: Cynodonteae): from northeastern Mexico. Journal of the Botanical Research Institute of Texas 1: 933 - 1000" title="Muhlenbergiinae (Poaceae: Chloridoideae: Cynodonteae): from northeastern Mexico." volume="1" year="2007 b">Peterson et al. 2007b</bibRefCitation>
). These results suggest multiple origins for 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. romaschenkoi" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="romaschenkoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">M. romaschenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from North and South American progenitors. Similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. caxamarcenis" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="caxamarcenis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">M. caxamarcenis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this scenario appears to be a common pattern of speciation for South American species of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia" order="Poales" pageId="56" pageNumber="179" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="179">Muhlenbergia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, needing further study.
</paragraph>
